alogy of Fallot","Ventricular septal defect","Coarctation of the aorta"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn cyanotic congenital heart defects, deoxygenated blood bypasses the pulmonary circulation and enters the systemic circulation (a right-to-left shunt), causing cyanosis. \u003Cstrong\u003ETetralogy of Fallot\u003C/strong\u003E is a classic cyanotic heart defect characterized by pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, overriding aorta, and ventricular septal defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are acyanotic heart defects with left-to-right shunting, or obstruction:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatent ductus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E allows blood to flow from the aorta to the pulmonary artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E allows blood to flow from the left to right atrium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E allows blood to flow from the left to right ventricle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoarctation of the aorta\u003C/strong\u003E is an obstruction of the aorta without shunting\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cyanotic heart defects involve right-to-left shunting of deoxygenated blood into the systemic circulation","Tetralogy of Fallot is a cyanotic congenital heart defect characterized by four key abnormalities","Patent ductus arteriosus, atrial septal defect, and ventricular septal defect are acyanotic left-to-right shunts"],"references":["Wilson R, Ross O, Griksaitis MJ. Tetralogy of Fallot. BJA Educ. 2019 Nov;19(11):362-369. doi: 10.1016/j.bjae.2019.07.003. Epub 2019 Oct 14. PMID: 33456859; PMCID: PMC7807827.","Hayes-Lattin M, Salmi D. Educational Case: Tetralogy of Fallot 